<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-485-319  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 485 319.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Oct 1 1990 v36 n1829 p29(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>EW vendors looking offshore after next two big DOD pacts.andO;(electronic warfare vendors to bid on foreign military contractsas US Department of Defense budget cuts limit US weaponsprocurements)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Electronic warfare vendors at the Association of Old Crows annualconvention in Boston say that after the US Army next-generationAdvanced Tactical Radar Jammer (ATRJ) and Air Force EF-111AUpgrade, the only opportunities will be overseas.andP;  Pending DefenseDepartment budget cuts mean few electronic warfare procurementsare in the offing in the US, which means the firms will have toshift their focus to foreign military markets.andP;  ITT Avionics,Northrop, Raytheon and a team of Sanders/American ElectronicsLaboratories are contending for the ATRJ award, which is expectedto be made very soon.andP;  The winner of that contract will need toinvest significant amounts of its own money in the six-yeardevelopment program.andP;  Rockwell International/Autonetics and a teamled by Grumman Aerospace are bidding for the EF-111 Upgrade; theaward is expected to be made in the spring of 1991.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Weapons IndustryIndustry AnalysisMilitaryCompetitive BiddingDefense contractsUnited States. Department of DefenseAssociation of Old Crows.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>